00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:52.040
KEN WALKER: We just want to
know where that comes from?

00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:52.450
TYLER PERRY: Excuse
me, excuse me.

00:02:52.450 --> 00:02:53.150
The hard work?

00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:54.817
KEN WALKER: Like what
is that creative--

00:02:54.817 --> 00:02:57.070
not even just the hard work,
but the timely manner--

00:02:57.070 --> 00:02:57.295
DE'ARRA TAYLOR: The dedication.

00:02:57.295 --> 00:02:59.212
KEN WALKER: The dedication
to shoot this movie

00:02:59.212 --> 00:03:01.790
in a record-breaking
amount of days.

00:03:01.790 --> 00:03:04.610
TYLER PERRY: But the reason it
sat in the can for two years

00:03:04.610 --> 00:03:06.342
is because we did--

00:03:06.342 --> 00:03:07.550
we had just finished "Boo 2!"

00:03:07.550 --> 00:03:10.290
And I didn't want to go "Boo!,"
"Boo 2!," "Madea Funeral."

00:03:10.290 --> 00:03:12.200
So I put "Acrimony" in the
middle and "Nobody's Fool,"

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:13.617
and now I was ready
to release it.

00:03:13.617 --> 00:03:17.720
But the speed of it is-- you
ever look at somebody working

00:03:17.720 --> 00:03:19.220
and you go, this
doesn't make sense?

00:03:19.220 --> 00:03:21.560
Like a lot of times,
I've seen other people

00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:24.560
shoot movies, and how much
time it takes, the downtime.

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:25.640
I've seen a guy--

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:27.905
I was on set for this one
movie-- it wasn't my movie.

00:03:27.905 --> 00:03:29.780
And I got there-- they
called me in like 6:00

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:33.590
in the morning to
come and shoot.

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:35.943
By noon, I still
hadn't shot anything.

00:03:35.943 --> 00:03:37.610
By like 3:00, I'm
sitting in the trailer

00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:39.450
like, OK, what the
hell's going on here?

00:03:39.450 --> 00:03:42.120
So I go out, and the
director comes to set.

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:44.330
And he goes, I don't like
it, change all the lights.

00:03:44.330 --> 00:03:46.413
After I have been sitting
there for like 12 hours.

00:03:46.413 --> 00:03:48.075
That wasn't a good day for him.

00:03:48.075 --> 00:03:49.950
Because I'm thinking,
why didn't the director

00:03:49.950 --> 00:03:53.630
show up early that morning,
get it set, get what he needed,

00:03:53.630 --> 00:03:56.630
make sure it was right and
not waste everybody's time?

00:03:56.630 --> 00:03:58.010
I'm all about efficiency.

00:03:58.010 --> 00:03:59.010
And I'm all about--

00:03:59.010 --> 00:04:01.490
I have a great team,
so we all move quickly.

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:03.560
We have a shorthand
so it doesn't--

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:05.420
Like "The Have
and Have Nots," we

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:07.940
shoot an episode
and a half in a day.

00:04:07.940 --> 00:04:10.520
If that were like, let's
say, "Scandal" or "Empire,"

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:14.330
it takes them a week and
a half or 7 to 10 days

00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:15.710
to shoot one episode.

00:04:15.710 --> 00:04:17.839
I just gotta--

00:04:17.839 --> 00:04:19.039
I like to move.

00:04:19.039 --> 00:04:21.830
And as long as the actors can
keep up, it's a great thing.

