00:13:37.690 --> 00:13:39.648
KEN WALKER: So I guess
one of my final question

00:13:39.648 --> 00:13:42.060
is how do you want
Madea to be remembered?

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:45.990
I guess with this being her last
film, a lot of funny jokes--

00:13:45.990 --> 00:13:49.050
I know Madea very well,
a lot of crazy things

00:13:49.050 --> 00:13:50.880
she said, a lot of
inspirational things

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:53.287
she said in a very
messed up way.

00:13:53.287 --> 00:13:55.120
But a lot of things
have been inspirational.

00:13:55.120 --> 00:13:56.495
So how do you just
want her to be

00:13:56.495 --> 00:13:57.975
remembered on a larger scale?

00:13:57.975 --> 00:14:00.600
TYLER PERRY: When you do when I
look back at the body of work--

00:14:00.600 --> 00:14:02.975
when I look at all of it, I
realized the first few movies

00:14:02.975 --> 00:14:05.460
when I was talking about
abuse and getting over things

00:14:05.460 --> 00:14:07.830
and bad marriages, I was
actually subconsciously talking

00:14:07.830 --> 00:14:10.737
to my mother in my writing,
and I didn't get it

00:14:10.737 --> 00:14:11.820
until I looked back on it.

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:13.320
But what I want her
to be remembered

00:14:13.320 --> 00:14:17.010
as is this grandmother that made
you laugh, have a good time.

00:14:17.010 --> 00:14:18.760
Forget about the
man in the dress,

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:21.803
but just somebody who spoke
wisdoms, made people feel good,

00:14:21.803 --> 00:14:24.220
and made things lighter in
their life a little bit better.

00:14:24.220 --> 00:14:25.380
So that's my hope in it.

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:26.948
That's my hope in it, for sure.

00:14:26.948 --> 00:14:27.990
DE'ARRA TAYLOR: OK, cool.

00:14:27.990 --> 00:14:30.573
And my last question was-- well,
you kind of already answered,

00:14:30.573 --> 00:14:33.720
but like what is next for you?

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:34.905
TYLER PERRY: After this nap?

00:14:34.905 --> 00:14:35.780
DE'ARRA TAYLOR: Yeah.

00:14:35.780 --> 00:14:36.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:36.190 --> 00:14:37.273
KEN WALKER: After the nap.

00:14:37.273 --> 00:14:38.337
TYLER PERRY: Yeah.

00:14:38.337 --> 00:14:39.920
Again, right now,
it's about legacies.

00:14:39.920 --> 00:14:41.563
It's about what am
I leaving behind?

00:14:41.563 --> 00:14:42.480
It's about the studio.

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:43.560
It's about my son.

00:14:43.560 --> 00:14:45.570
It's about what is the legacy?

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:48.553
And how wide can I
hold this door open?

00:14:48.553 --> 00:14:50.970
Because I'm looking at what's
happening in Hollywood right

00:14:50.970 --> 00:14:52.553
now, and everybody's
like, oh, my god,

00:14:52.553 --> 00:14:54.450
diversity is so
amazing and great.

00:14:54.450 --> 00:14:56.430
It's like, Tyler, do you
think it's wonderful?

00:14:56.430 --> 00:14:58.800
But the truth is I
was doing diversity

00:14:58.800 --> 00:15:00.030
before diversity was cool.

00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:01.322
DE'ARRA TAYLOR: Right, I agree.

00:15:01.322 --> 00:15:04.590
TYLER PERRY: I was hiring
people like Idris Elba and Viola

00:15:04.590 --> 00:15:07.510
Davis, and Sofia Vergara, and
Kerry Washington, Taraji P.

00:15:07.510 --> 00:15:08.010
Henson.

00:15:08.010 --> 00:15:09.480
These people couldn't get work.

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:11.440
So now to look at
what's happening here--

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:13.200
I don't want people
to forget that there

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:16.500
was a fight from
many, many years

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:17.978
to get to where we are now.

00:15:17.978 --> 00:15:19.270
We still have a long way to go.

00:15:19.270 --> 00:15:23.970
But I'm seeing the nucleus
of a brilliant time, where

00:15:23.970 --> 00:15:26.220
all stories are being
able to be told.

00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:28.740
And the beauty of that is, I
realized that my criticism is

00:15:28.740 --> 00:15:29.730
a lot less.

00:15:29.730 --> 00:15:33.480
Because everybody gets a chance
to tell their stories now.

00:15:33.480 --> 00:15:34.890
When you're the
only black person

00:15:34.890 --> 00:15:38.010
out there telling
your stories, you've

00:15:38.010 --> 00:15:39.635
got black people
going what the hell?

00:15:39.635 --> 00:15:41.760
That's not me, that doesn't
represent black people.

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:43.802
But it represents the
black people I know, right?

00:15:43.802 --> 00:15:46.680
So now to see Issa
Rae and Donald Glover

00:15:46.680 --> 00:15:50.130
and Ryan Coogler
and all these people

00:15:50.130 --> 00:15:52.107
get to tell their stories,
I'm just in heaven.

00:15:52.107 --> 00:15:54.690
So I just want to keep holding
the door open as wide as I can.

00:15:54.690 --> 00:15:55.607
DE'ARRA TAYLOR: Great.

00:15:55.607 --> 00:15:56.370
KEN WALKER: Nice.

00:15:56.370 --> 00:15:58.470
So we're going to open
it up to the audience.

00:15:58.470 --> 00:16:00.270
You guys have any
questions about Madea,

00:16:00.270 --> 00:16:02.670
"Madea's Family
Funeral," anything

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:04.570
of the matter, anything.

00:16:04.570 --> 00:16:05.277
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:16:05.277 --> 00:16:05.985
TYLER PERRY: Hey.

00:16:05.985 --> 00:16:07.460
AUDIENCE: Hey,
Tyler, LaToya Drake.

00:16:07.460 --> 00:16:09.170
I work here at Google.

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:12.080
I grew up in Georgia, so
shout out to the state.

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:13.820
It's really encouraging
to see everything

00:16:13.820 --> 00:16:15.740
that you've done
with the studio, all

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:19.010
the economic prosperity
you've brought to the state.

00:16:19.010 --> 00:16:21.350
After the
gubernatorial election,

00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:23.810
there was talk of Hollywood
pulling its dollars

00:16:23.810 --> 00:16:25.820
as a reaction to
Brian Kemp winning.

00:16:25.820 --> 00:16:27.578
Wondering what
crossed your mind,

00:16:27.578 --> 00:16:29.120
if that was something
you considered,

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:32.060
or how you felt you needed
to react to that move

00:16:32.060 --> 00:16:33.365
to take our dollars away?

00:16:33.365 --> 00:16:34.160
TYLER PERRY: Yeah.

00:16:34.160 --> 00:16:35.840
Well, listen, I'm
glad people didn't,

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:38.810
because it's so important
for so many people that

00:16:38.810 --> 00:16:39.560
are working there.

00:16:39.560 --> 00:16:42.310
And I've fought so hard to have
the tax credit and everything

00:16:42.310 --> 00:16:42.810
else.

00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:45.317
And I hate when politics
starts to dictate

00:16:45.317 --> 00:16:46.400
what happens in the state.

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:48.230
Because there are so
many good people there.

00:16:48.230 --> 00:16:49.938
There's so many people
who have never had

00:16:49.938 --> 00:16:52.380
an opportunity in the business.

00:16:52.380 --> 00:16:55.760
The great thing about
what is happening now

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:57.857
as I'm watching
Stacey in her fight,

00:16:57.857 --> 00:16:59.690
and what recently
happened in North Carolina

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:02.570
with a new election-- as long
as Stacey keeps up her fight,

00:17:02.570 --> 00:17:03.358
I'm on her side.

00:17:03.358 --> 00:17:05.150
I'm right there in her
corner so that there

00:17:05.150 --> 00:17:07.740
can be a fair and balanced
moment in all of this,

00:17:07.740 --> 00:17:08.240
for sure.

00:17:08.240 --> 00:17:09.641
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:17:13.972 --> 00:17:15.930
TYLER PERRY: I think you
have to go to the mic.

00:17:15.930 --> 00:17:18.684
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:18.684 --> 00:17:20.520
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:22.359
Thank you for coming.

00:17:22.359 --> 00:17:23.602
You wear a lot of hats.

00:17:23.602 --> 00:17:25.560
You're the director, and
writer, and producer--

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:26.359
TYLER PERRY: And
a couple of wigs.

00:17:26.359 --> 00:17:27.339
AUDIENCE: And a
couple wigs, yeah.

00:17:27.339 --> 00:17:28.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:28.230 --> 00:17:31.380
Is there anything
maybe inside or outside

00:17:31.380 --> 00:17:32.880
of show business
that you want to do

00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:33.963
that you haven't done yet?

00:17:33.963 --> 00:17:35.797
TYLER PERRY: No, the
great thing about it is

00:17:35.797 --> 00:17:37.140
I've been fortunate enough to--

00:17:37.140 --> 00:17:38.920
because if I wasn't in the
business, I'd be an architect.

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:39.687
I love designing.

00:17:39.687 --> 00:17:42.270
So I've been fortunate enough
to be able to design the studio,

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:44.310
design my house, design
different places.

00:17:44.310 --> 00:17:46.410
That's what I would
be doing, so it's

00:17:46.410 --> 00:17:48.330
awesome to be in
a position where

00:17:48.330 --> 00:17:51.910
one thing can afford you to do
everything else you want to do.

00:17:51.910 --> 00:17:55.980
And also, this was a really,
really, really big dream

00:17:55.980 --> 00:17:58.710
of mine, but I'm not
sure that I'm ever

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:02.250
going to get a chance to do
it because I'm older now.

00:18:02.250 --> 00:18:05.484
But I want to win a gold medal
in the Olympics as a gymnast.

00:18:05.484 --> 00:18:06.798
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:06.798 --> 00:18:07.840
I'm kidding, I'm kidding.

00:18:07.840 --> 00:18:09.160
AUDIENCE: You're this close.

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:10.035
TYLER PERRY: Kidding.

00:18:10.035 --> 00:18:13.245
Yeah, this close, this
close, this close.

00:18:13.245 --> 00:18:14.870
AUDIENCE: Hi, Tyler,
thanks for coming.

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:16.470
TYLER PERRY: Oh,
it's my pleasure.

00:18:16.470 --> 00:18:18.270
AUDIENCE: So looking
at your career,

00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:20.610
one of the most
amazing things about it

00:18:20.610 --> 00:18:24.720
is really, the way that you've
tapped into your imagination

00:18:24.720 --> 00:18:27.570
to unlock all these
different possibilities.

00:18:27.570 --> 00:18:31.260
And it's a powerful thing
that I think not enough people

00:18:31.260 --> 00:18:32.850
spend time doing.

00:18:32.850 --> 00:18:34.620
And so thinking
about your career,

00:18:34.620 --> 00:18:38.040
just as an actor, and
then stage, and then film,

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:40.020
and then for most
actors, the big step

00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:41.370
is going behind the camera.

00:18:41.370 --> 00:18:45.690
And you're like, screw that, I'm
going to get a studio, and then

00:18:45.690 --> 00:18:48.400
partner with Marvel and
all these other companies.

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:51.090
And so for me, I'm just
curious about your process

00:18:51.090 --> 00:18:55.170
for unlocking your imagination
and then perceiving things,

00:18:55.170 --> 00:18:57.918
or trying to achieve things
that would seem monumental.

00:18:57.918 --> 00:18:59.460
TYLER PERRY: Here's
the thing for me.

00:18:59.460 --> 00:19:00.510
I was praying one
day, and I said,

00:19:00.510 --> 00:19:02.760
God, I don't want to leave
this planet until I've done

00:19:02.760 --> 00:19:04.390
everything I'm supposed to do.

00:19:04.390 --> 00:19:06.720
And this level of the
studio-- the one I

00:19:06.720 --> 00:19:10.830
had before this was about
30 acres, six soundstages.

00:19:10.830 --> 00:19:11.820
I was comfortable, man.

00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:13.530
I was so happy there.

00:19:13.530 --> 00:19:14.280
Everything's good.

00:19:14.280 --> 00:19:16.113
I was shooting all "The
Have and Have Nots."

00:19:16.113 --> 00:19:17.580
I'm like, yes, this is it!

00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:19.800
But then I got that nudge
that it's time to grow,

00:19:19.800 --> 00:19:20.700
it's time to move.

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:23.010
And you've got to be careful
when you get comfortable

00:19:23.010 --> 00:19:23.880
in a situation.

00:19:23.880 --> 00:19:26.880
Because things will start to
fall apart if you don't move.

00:19:26.880 --> 00:19:28.740
This is what I found
just in my prayer life,

00:19:28.740 --> 00:19:33.870
that I'm getting hits to
move, if I don't, things

00:19:33.870 --> 00:19:35.230
start to fall apart.

00:19:35.230 --> 00:19:36.900
So I move into this new studio.

00:19:36.900 --> 00:19:38.310
I didn't want to.

00:19:38.310 --> 00:19:40.620
But now looking back at
it three years into it,

00:19:40.620 --> 00:19:43.180
now I go OK, this was beyond me.

00:19:43.180 --> 00:19:44.017
It's bigger than me.

00:19:44.017 --> 00:19:46.600
So you have to understand that
when you get the opportunities,

00:19:46.600 --> 00:19:48.000
they're not just for you.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:49.620
Sometimes what's
happening for you

00:19:49.620 --> 00:19:51.607
is for the next person,
and the next person,

00:19:51.607 --> 00:19:52.440
and the next person.

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:55.080
And your example can
change their lives.

00:19:55.080 --> 00:19:57.420
So holding that in
the front of my mind

00:19:57.420 --> 00:20:00.332
has been so important every
time I get ready to go.

00:20:00.332 --> 00:20:02.040
Because I've gotten
to a place in my life

00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:04.470
like-- look, turning 50, I
just want to go sit on a beach

00:20:04.470 --> 00:20:05.595
and smoke some weed, right?

00:20:05.595 --> 00:20:06.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:06.260 --> 00:20:09.840
But now-- it's truth, truth.

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:11.420
But you're too young
to do that, son.

00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:12.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:12.330 --> 00:20:16.530
But the truth is
making sure that I'm

00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:18.690
being faithful and
loyal to everything

00:20:18.690 --> 00:20:19.690
that I'm supposed to do.

00:20:19.690 --> 00:20:21.690
Because a lot of times, your
visions are tied into the next

00:20:21.690 --> 00:20:22.290
person's.

00:20:22.290 --> 00:20:23.832
So I hope that
answers your question.

00:20:23.832 --> 00:20:25.477
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:20:25.477 --> 00:20:27.060
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for being with us.

00:20:27.060 --> 00:20:27.600
TYLER PERRY: Oh,
it's my pleasure.

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:29.680
AUDIENCE: I have two questions.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:31.650
You mentioned the
speed of your work

00:20:31.650 --> 00:20:33.750
and how fast you
get things done.

00:20:33.750 --> 00:20:37.770
Did that affect the
quality of the production

00:20:37.770 --> 00:20:39.570
in any department?

00:20:39.570 --> 00:20:41.180
Second question is--

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:42.750
I'm a YouTube musician.

00:20:42.750 --> 00:20:46.420
And we've seen you before
work with YouTube influencers.

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:49.440
And I've been humbled getting
noticed by the great Quincy

00:20:49.440 --> 00:20:50.410
Jones and Sia.

00:20:50.410 --> 00:20:52.860
Do you have any plans
in the future working

00:20:52.860 --> 00:20:54.390
with YouTube musicians as well?

00:20:54.390 --> 00:20:55.110
TYLER PERRY: Working with--

00:20:55.110 --> 00:20:55.780
I'm sorry, what's the last part?

00:20:55.780 --> 00:20:56.580
AUDIENCE: YouTube musicians.

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:57.390
TYLER PERRY: Oh wow.

00:20:57.390 --> 00:20:58.682
AUDIENCE: Not just influencers.

00:20:58.682 --> 00:21:00.360
TYLER PERRY: That
would be incredible.

00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:03.030
Dude, let me answer the
first part of your question.

00:21:03.030 --> 00:21:05.860
You look at it, you tell me.

00:21:05.860 --> 00:21:09.415
I look at my movie that compare
it to other movies like that,

00:21:09.415 --> 00:21:10.000
right?

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.560
And I think,
nothing's suffering.

00:21:11.560 --> 00:21:13.720
There's no quality is suffering.

00:21:13.720 --> 00:21:14.770
They look beautiful.

00:21:14.770 --> 00:21:16.812
The sound is beautiful,
the lighting's beautiful.

00:21:16.812 --> 00:21:19.510
It's compared to everything
else in that space.

00:21:19.510 --> 00:21:21.135
Now if I was making
"Schindler's List,"

00:21:21.135 --> 00:21:22.718
then we'd have to
have a conversation.

00:21:22.718 --> 00:21:23.358
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:23.358 --> 00:21:24.900
Because I can't do
that in five days.

00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:26.400
There's a process there.

00:21:26.400 --> 00:21:29.350
And if I was working with
a cinematographer who

00:21:29.350 --> 00:21:31.510
wanted the sun to
fall just perfectly

00:21:31.510 --> 00:21:33.790
over her beautiful
hair and lashes,

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:36.850
and we have to shoot
this scene on Thursday

00:21:36.850 --> 00:21:40.570
at 4:36 in the evening,
not a second later,

00:21:40.570 --> 00:21:42.410
then it would be
a different thing.

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:44.390
This is Madea, you
know what I mean?

00:21:44.390 --> 00:21:44.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:44.890 --> 00:21:46.810
So I take it for what it is.

00:21:46.810 --> 00:21:49.570
But no, I wrote a piece
that I wanted to play.

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:51.150
I wrote it in 1995.

00:21:51.150 --> 00:21:52.660
It's called "A
Jazz Man's Blues."

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:55.810
It's about a jazz singer and
a Holocaust survivor, big band

00:21:55.810 --> 00:21:56.860
music.

00:21:56.860 --> 00:21:59.720
And I wanted to play the role,
but I've aged out of it now.

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:01.837
So I have to hire somebody
else to play the role.

00:22:01.837 --> 00:22:03.670
But as I'm thinking
about big band and jazz,

00:22:03.670 --> 00:22:08.233
I'll start looking
at YouTube musicians.

00:22:08.233 --> 00:22:10.400
That'll be really good to
think about, so thank you.

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:11.233
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:22:11.233 --> 00:22:13.525
TYLER PERRY: Thank you.

00:22:13.525 --> 00:22:15.356
AUDIENCE: I'm too
short for this.

00:22:15.356 --> 00:22:16.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:16.940
Hi.

00:22:16.940 --> 00:22:17.210
TYLER PERRY: Hi.

00:22:17.210 --> 00:22:18.543
AUDIENCE: My name's Shayla Byrd.

00:22:18.543 --> 00:22:22.550
I am actually the only full time
black writer here at Google New

00:22:22.550 --> 00:22:23.460
York.

00:22:23.460 --> 00:22:26.250
And so I took this job because
I'm really into writing.

00:22:26.250 --> 00:22:27.920
But as I've been
working here, there's

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:30.512
so many things like logistical
things, and meeting,

00:22:30.512 --> 00:22:32.720
and strategy, and all these
other things that kind of

00:22:32.720 --> 00:22:33.580
come along with it.

00:22:33.580 --> 00:22:35.312
So I look to you as
someone who created

00:22:35.312 --> 00:22:36.770
this amazing
character, who created

00:22:36.770 --> 00:22:39.480
this cultural phenomenon.

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:42.212
And I'm wondering how do
you structure your life

00:22:42.212 --> 00:22:43.920
or make sure that you
are able to hold on

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:48.680
to the creative things that
you enjoy while also running

00:22:48.680 --> 00:22:50.300
your business?

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:51.050
TYLER PERRY: Yeah.

00:22:51.050 --> 00:22:51.680
AUDIENCE: How do you
hold on to things--

00:22:51.680 --> 00:22:53.430
TYLER PERRY: You have
to nurture the both.

00:22:53.430 --> 00:22:56.390
Like for me, you
make space for them.

00:22:56.390 --> 00:23:00.080
Like when I write, I have
to go to a certain place,

00:23:00.080 --> 00:23:02.600
then let the writer speak,
let the writer feel free,

00:23:02.600 --> 00:23:03.740
let the writer do
what he wants to do.

00:23:03.740 --> 00:23:04.850
That's the one who
wants to smoke weed.

00:23:04.850 --> 00:23:06.410
My business guy
doesn't smoke weed.

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:09.350
But the writer-- that
guy-- let him be.

00:23:09.350 --> 00:23:11.540
So you compartmentalize.

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:13.780
Like for me, my brain has--

00:23:13.780 --> 00:23:15.290
I want all sides of it to work.

00:23:15.290 --> 00:23:17.760
So this moment, I'm
going to just write.

00:23:17.760 --> 00:23:19.310
I'm going to take this time,
and I'm just going to write.

00:23:19.310 --> 00:23:20.360
That's all I'm going to do.

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:22.310
Then when I'm directing,
I just want to direct.

00:23:22.310 --> 00:23:23.685
And when I'm
running the business

00:23:23.685 --> 00:23:26.910
or signing monthly checks,
that's where my focus is.

00:23:26.910 --> 00:23:29.810
So what I would
suggest is that you

00:23:29.810 --> 00:23:32.980
make sure that the writer
has its space, its time,

00:23:32.980 --> 00:23:37.730
and to protect her so that she
can be as creative as she wants

00:23:37.730 --> 00:23:39.600
to be however she wants to be.

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:41.900
And allow her that [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:41.900 --> 00:23:44.795
Like this is time for
this specifically, period.

00:23:44.795 --> 00:23:46.670
And then let the business
side of it be that.

00:23:46.670 --> 00:23:47.620
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:23:47.620 --> 00:23:48.250
TYLER PERRY: Make sense?

00:23:48.250 --> 00:23:48.650
AUDIENCE: Yeah, it does.

00:23:48.650 --> 00:23:48.860
TYLER PERRY: OK, OK.

00:23:48.860 --> 00:23:50.228
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:23:50.228 --> 00:23:51.463
AUDIENCE: Hi, Tyler.

00:23:51.463 --> 00:23:52.130
TYLER PERRY: Hi.

00:23:52.130 --> 00:23:54.000
AUDIENCE: I'm [INAUDIBLE],,
I work here at Google.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:55.010
Thank you so much for coming.

00:23:55.010 --> 00:23:56.090
TYLER PERRY: Oh,
it's my pleasure.

00:23:56.090 --> 00:23:56.960
Everybody work at Google?

00:23:56.960 --> 00:23:57.840
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:23:57.840 --> 00:23:59.923
TYLER PERRY: Yeah, that's
awesome, that's awesome.

00:23:59.923 --> 00:24:02.705
AUDIENCE: I recently saw
"Boo!" with 20 of my cousins.

00:24:02.705 --> 00:24:05.205
I just told them that I met
you, so they're all going crazy.

00:24:05.205 --> 00:24:06.140
TYLER PERRY: That's awesome.

00:24:06.140 --> 00:24:07.820
AUDIENCE: Latin
audiences love you.

00:24:07.820 --> 00:24:11.780
My question is for
people that are looking

00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:16.340
to get into the space of
content production, what

00:24:16.340 --> 00:24:18.350
would be the simplest
piece of advice

00:24:18.350 --> 00:24:21.920
that you would give to someone
wanting to get into the space,

00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:25.220
thinking about all of the areas
that are disrupting the space,

00:24:25.220 --> 00:24:26.420
right?

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:29.240
You have technology, you
have YouTube creators.

00:24:29.240 --> 00:24:31.328
You have so many
Hollywood actors

00:24:31.328 --> 00:24:32.870
that are already in
the space, and so

00:24:32.870 --> 00:24:34.028
many production companies.

00:24:34.028 --> 00:24:35.570
What would be the
one piece of advice

00:24:35.570 --> 00:24:36.530
that you would give to someone?

00:24:36.530 --> 00:24:37.760
TYLER PERRY: Tell me what
space you're talking about.

00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:38.260
Entertainment?

00:24:38.260 --> 00:24:39.230
AUDIENCE: So creating--

00:24:39.230 --> 00:24:39.660
TYLER PERRY: Show business?

00:24:39.660 --> 00:24:41.327
AUDIENCE: --making a
movie, for example.

00:24:41.327 --> 00:24:43.763
TYLER PERRY: Yeah, listen,
with technology today,

00:24:43.763 --> 00:24:45.680
you can take an iPhone
and make a great movie.

00:24:45.680 --> 00:24:48.810
So I think everything
is so open now,

00:24:48.810 --> 00:24:52.910
it's such a great time for
creators, or content creators,

00:24:52.910 --> 00:24:53.900
for artists.

00:24:53.900 --> 00:24:57.290
Whatever your uniqueness is,
if you have a story that you

00:24:57.290 --> 00:24:58.660
think is so special--

00:24:58.660 --> 00:25:00.320
listen, my first
play, I put every dime

00:25:00.320 --> 00:25:01.570
I had into it to make it work.

00:25:01.570 --> 00:25:04.190
And I think now with
all of these platforms

00:25:04.190 --> 00:25:06.440
that you can place
them on, you're

00:25:06.440 --> 00:25:09.602
exposing your talent to
millions and millions of people.

00:25:09.602 --> 00:25:11.060
And I think that's
the best way in.

00:25:11.060 --> 00:25:13.550
That's the best way in,
to invest in yourself,

00:25:13.550 --> 00:25:15.350
show something different,
something unique,

00:25:15.350 --> 00:25:17.580
and make people go,
wow, what is that?

00:25:17.580 --> 00:25:21.320
End up with 7 1/2 million
followers just looking at what

00:25:21.320 --> 00:25:22.960
you're doing from day to day.

00:25:22.960 --> 00:25:23.860
So that's the way in.

00:25:23.860 --> 00:25:25.127
It's a whole new world now.

00:25:25.127 --> 00:25:25.960
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:27.127
TYLER PERRY: Yeah, for sure.

00:25:27.127 --> 00:25:27.920
Thank you.

00:25:27.920 --> 00:25:29.300
Tell all 20 cousins I said hi.

00:25:29.300 --> 00:25:30.008
AUDIENCE: I will.

00:25:30.008 --> 00:25:30.716
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:30.716 --> 00:25:32.720
AUDIENCE: Hey, I'm Omar,
I'm a high schooler

00:25:32.720 --> 00:25:33.540
and I'm a YouTuber.

00:25:33.540 --> 00:25:36.410
So I was just wondering if
you had any piece of advice

00:25:36.410 --> 00:25:38.720
that you wish you knew when
you were in high school,

00:25:38.720 --> 00:25:41.263
trying to become a filmmaker
and trying to become an actor?

00:25:41.263 --> 00:25:43.430
TYLER PERRY: You know what
I wish I would have done?

00:25:43.430 --> 00:25:44.722
I wish I'd have took more time.

00:25:47.860 --> 00:25:50.870
OK, I know you're in school,
I shouldn't say this to you.

00:25:50.870 --> 00:25:53.450
But the algebra you're probably
not going use very much,

00:25:53.450 --> 00:25:54.075
unless you're--

00:25:54.075 --> 00:25:54.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:57.952
But I wish that I had
done better in school

00:25:57.952 --> 00:25:58.910
and went on to college.

00:25:58.910 --> 00:26:01.790
Because I've paid for
a Harvard education

00:26:01.790 --> 00:26:04.220
50 times in all the
mistakes that I've made.

00:26:04.220 --> 00:26:05.930
So I didn't realize
that everything

00:26:05.930 --> 00:26:07.940
that I was learning
in high school

00:26:07.940 --> 00:26:09.810
would have been
so important now.

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:12.970
So what I would say to
you is the education

00:26:12.970 --> 00:26:13.970
is going to be key, man.

00:26:13.970 --> 00:26:17.350
Go on to college to get every
bit of knowledge you can

00:26:17.350 --> 00:26:19.100
so that you don't end
up like me, spending

00:26:19.100 --> 00:26:21.517
that kind of money, two, three,
four, five times on things

00:26:21.517 --> 00:26:23.630
that you could have
learned by going to school

00:26:23.630 --> 00:26:26.290
for a few semesters, you know?

00:26:26.290 --> 00:26:28.290
And because you're
here, which me tells me

00:26:28.290 --> 00:26:30.380
you're pretty smart, so
I would hold onto that.

00:26:30.380 --> 00:26:33.440
Just stay in school, get as
much knowledge as you can,

00:26:33.440 --> 00:26:37.720
so when you go on out there
to do whatever you're doing,

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:40.687
that bit of education will
help take you a long way.

00:26:40.687 --> 00:26:41.520
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:44.087
TYLER PERRY: I know it sounds
cliche, but true, so true.

00:26:44.087 --> 00:26:44.920
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:26:44.920 --> 00:26:46.100
TYLER PERRY: But
the algebra ain't

00:26:46.100 --> 00:26:47.892
going to help you much
unless you're just--

00:26:47.892 --> 00:26:48.425
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:48.425 --> 00:26:50.300
AUDIENCE: Hey, Tyler,
Jose, nice to meet you.

00:26:50.300 --> 00:26:51.258
TYLER PERRY: Hey, Jose.

00:26:51.258 --> 00:26:53.230
AUDIENCE: You talked a
little bit about legacy.

00:26:53.230 --> 00:26:57.590
And you've had the privilege
of seeing your success get you

00:26:57.590 --> 00:27:00.142
to a platform where
now you can think back

00:27:00.142 --> 00:27:01.100
and think about legacy.

00:27:01.100 --> 00:27:02.940
So my question is
kind of multi-fold.

00:27:02.940 --> 00:27:04.610
But when you look
back and you think

00:27:04.610 --> 00:27:08.300
about your mentors and each
stage that you were in,

00:27:08.300 --> 00:27:09.950
were the mentors the same?

00:27:09.950 --> 00:27:11.608
Did they change at all?

00:27:11.608 --> 00:27:13.400
And when you think
about where you are now,

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:15.260
who are your
mentors, and who are

00:27:15.260 --> 00:27:16.910
you pouring into as a mentor?

00:27:16.910 --> 00:27:19.360
TYLER PERRY: Wow.

00:27:19.360 --> 00:27:20.920
Mentors, that's
a great question.

00:27:20.920 --> 00:27:22.428
My mentors-- all
of a sudden, I feel

00:27:22.428 --> 00:27:23.720
like I'm running for president.

00:27:23.720 --> 00:27:25.928
Yeah, that was a great
question from Jose, thank you.

00:27:25.928 --> 00:27:27.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:27.020 --> 00:27:29.420
I want to talk to all the
men and women of America.

00:27:29.420 --> 00:27:33.080
But my mentors
coming up were Oprah,

00:27:33.080 --> 00:27:37.490
and people like her and Maya
Angelou-- just the wisdoms,

00:27:37.490 --> 00:27:38.950
I loved wisdoms--

00:27:38.950 --> 00:27:41.690
and Nelson Mandela.

00:27:41.690 --> 00:27:44.310
And getting a chance
to meet those people

00:27:44.310 --> 00:27:47.960
and see them, and hear them
talk about how I inspired them,

00:27:47.960 --> 00:27:51.250
it was really mind-blowing
for me, right?

00:27:51.250 --> 00:27:55.310
So Maya's passed on,
and Nelson's passed on.

00:27:55.310 --> 00:27:58.460
Oprah's still here,
and thank God.

00:27:58.460 --> 00:27:59.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:01.060
Wait, did something happen
and y'all ain't tell me?

00:28:01.060 --> 00:28:01.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:01.940
No, no, she's fine.

00:28:01.940 --> 00:28:04.273
No, she's fine, I just talked
to her a little while ago.

00:28:04.273 --> 00:28:05.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:07.490 --> 00:28:09.350
Now she's still a mentor.

00:28:09.350 --> 00:28:10.935
TD Jakes is a mentor.

00:28:10.935 --> 00:28:12.560
Spiritual growth is
so important to me,

00:28:12.560 --> 00:28:14.300
so all of these people
who have wisdoms--

00:28:14.300 --> 00:28:15.860
just bring me wisdoms.

00:28:15.860 --> 00:28:18.200
And what I'm trying to do
at this point in my life

00:28:18.200 --> 00:28:23.732
is be more open to other
people, just to be open enough

00:28:23.732 --> 00:28:25.940
to understand that there
are so many other people who

00:28:25.940 --> 00:28:26.810
have something to bring.

00:28:26.810 --> 00:28:28.268
And everybody
teaches you something

00:28:28.268 --> 00:28:30.110
in this life, everybody.

00:28:30.110 --> 00:28:30.763
Everybody.

00:28:30.763 --> 00:28:32.180
Everybody you come
in contact with

00:28:32.180 --> 00:28:34.953
can teach you something one way
or another, good or bad, right,

00:28:34.953 --> 00:28:35.870
wrong, or indifferent.

00:28:35.870 --> 00:28:37.070
I don't believe that
anybody shows up

00:28:37.070 --> 00:28:38.987
in your life that is not
supposed to be there.

00:28:38.987 --> 00:28:41.780
Either it's to press to
make you stronger or better

00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:43.307
or to depress you.

00:28:43.307 --> 00:28:45.390
But whatever it is, it's
going to make you better.

00:28:45.390 --> 00:28:49.462
So what I say to you is--

00:28:49.462 --> 00:28:50.630
my mic just went out.

00:28:50.630 --> 00:28:51.520
That reminded me of the Oscars.

00:28:51.520 --> 00:28:52.560
Is it time for me to go?

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:53.820
Are they about start
playing the music?

00:28:53.820 --> 00:28:54.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:54.590 --> 00:28:56.640
So what I would say to
you is that those people

00:28:56.640 --> 00:28:57.307
are [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:57.307 --> 00:28:59.070
And as far as mentoring,
you see that kid

00:28:59.070 --> 00:29:01.390
back there on the camera there?

00:29:01.390 --> 00:29:04.170
He's one of them.

00:29:04.170 --> 00:29:06.560
And I have tons of
people at the studio who

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:10.020
are young and fresh and
excited, and who never

00:29:10.020 --> 00:29:11.640
had the opportunity before.

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:13.840
And they're walking
through those gates going,

00:29:13.840 --> 00:29:16.350
a black man owns this?

00:29:16.350 --> 00:29:17.310
What?

00:29:17.310 --> 00:29:19.535
And for them, it's
like what it would

00:29:19.535 --> 00:29:21.910
have been like for me walking
into somebody else's space,

00:29:21.910 --> 00:29:24.730
going wow, letting them know
that anything's possible.

00:29:24.730 --> 00:29:29.370
I mean, this army base was
once a Confederate army base.

00:29:29.370 --> 00:29:33.105
To be owned by a black
man, it's shocking.

00:29:33.105 --> 00:29:34.320
[APPLAUSE]

00:29:34.320 --> 00:29:36.900
So I think all of that
speaks to mentoring.

00:29:36.900 --> 00:29:37.400
OK.

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:38.233
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:29:38.233 --> 00:29:40.020
TYLER PERRY: Thank you.

00:29:40.020 --> 00:29:41.520
AUDIENCE: Hello,
my name is Angela.

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:42.330
TYLER PERRY: Hi,
Angela, how you doing?

00:29:42.330 --> 00:29:44.310
AUDIENCE: And I've actually been
to-- since everybody's saying

00:29:44.310 --> 00:29:45.060
their connection--

00:29:45.060 --> 00:29:48.233
I went to Tyler Perry Studios in
2012 for the Obama fundraiser.

00:29:48.233 --> 00:29:49.275
TYLER PERRY: Obama, yeah.

00:29:49.275 --> 00:29:51.030
AUDIENCE: And that was
before I worked at Google,

00:29:51.030 --> 00:29:53.460
and so I scraped all my
change together to get there.

00:29:53.460 --> 00:29:55.010
But it was a great experience.

00:29:55.010 --> 00:29:55.930
TYLER PERRY: I love
how she said it.

00:29:55.930 --> 00:29:56.770
It was before I
worked at Google,

00:29:56.770 --> 00:29:58.050
because now I'm at Google,
I got a little money,

00:29:58.050 --> 00:29:58.920
I could go down--

00:29:58.920 --> 00:29:59.920
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:29:59.920 --> 00:30:00.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:00.420 --> 00:30:02.410
AUDIENCE: I made it a
little bit [INAUDIBLE]..

00:30:02.410 --> 00:30:04.780
But that was a great experience.

00:30:04.780 --> 00:30:07.930
I'd love for you to speak
more about your early days,

00:30:07.930 --> 00:30:12.520
and talk about more the
communities and churches

00:30:12.520 --> 00:30:15.467
and groups that supported
your early work, the circuit

00:30:15.467 --> 00:30:16.300
that you're running.

00:30:16.300 --> 00:30:19.300
I mean, you're writing the
plays and performing them

00:30:19.300 --> 00:30:23.530
where really, local communities
and churches who thought it

00:30:23.530 --> 00:30:24.470
was funny.

00:30:24.470 --> 00:30:26.410
So I'd love to hear you just
talk more about that experience

00:30:26.410 --> 00:30:28.840
and what it was like getting the
word out among that community,

00:30:28.840 --> 00:30:30.580
and then how you're also
remembering those communities

00:30:30.580 --> 00:30:32.110
that supported
you in those days,

00:30:32.110 --> 00:30:34.120
and what you're doing with them.

00:30:34.120 --> 00:30:34.960
TYLER PERRY: Let's
start with community.

00:30:34.960 --> 00:30:36.752
Because you talk about
being there in 2012.

00:30:36.752 --> 00:30:37.810
That was the old studio.

00:30:37.810 --> 00:30:40.570
You've got to see
the new one, whew!

00:30:40.570 --> 00:30:41.780
But I'll never forget that.

00:30:41.780 --> 00:30:44.530
You talk about how I'm
supporting community by just

00:30:44.530 --> 00:30:45.820
building in the community.

00:30:45.820 --> 00:30:48.940
Because it's in one of the
poorest areas in Atlanta.

00:30:48.940 --> 00:30:50.978
The median income is
about $25,000 a year.

00:30:50.978 --> 00:30:52.270
Nobody really owns their house.

00:30:52.270 --> 00:30:55.210
When the army base
closed in 2011,

00:30:55.210 --> 00:30:57.320
it left the place decimated.

00:30:57.320 --> 00:31:03.790
So to build in that
area is so powerful.

00:31:03.790 --> 00:31:07.000
To build among black people,
the ones that supported me,

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.840
the ones that put me
here, is so powerful.

00:31:09.840 --> 00:31:12.730
And I'll never forget that
day when President Obama came.

00:31:12.730 --> 00:31:14.590
He was the sitting
president, coming

00:31:14.590 --> 00:31:16.750
to the poorest part of Atlanta.

00:31:16.750 --> 00:31:18.250
The motorcade comes
down the street,

00:31:18.250 --> 00:31:20.542
and I'm looking at all these
little black faces holding

00:31:20.542 --> 00:31:22.810
these flags, these kids
waving them, just thinking,

00:31:22.810 --> 00:31:25.780
they never would have
seen this had I not

00:31:25.780 --> 00:31:27.610
put the studio right here.

00:31:27.610 --> 00:31:30.700
So building in community and
hiring from the community

00:31:30.700 --> 00:31:33.130
has been so important to
us, pulling people in so

00:31:33.130 --> 00:31:34.720
that they know and take pride.

00:31:34.720 --> 00:31:37.990
And I'll never forget, I
was coming to work one day

00:31:37.990 --> 00:31:42.860
and this woman was out
picking up trash in the grass.

00:31:42.860 --> 00:31:45.910
And I stopped, I was
like, hi, you need a job?

00:31:45.910 --> 00:31:46.480
We're hiring.

00:31:46.480 --> 00:31:50.200
She said, no, I work for the
federal government, I'm good.

00:31:50.200 --> 00:31:52.580
I'm like, you're just
picking up the trash?

00:31:52.580 --> 00:31:55.635
She said, yeah, yeah, because
you're in the neighborhood.

00:31:55.635 --> 00:31:57.010
And you did a
beautiful job here,

00:31:57.010 --> 00:31:58.780
and we want you to
know how thankful we

00:31:58.780 --> 00:32:00.257
are that you're here with us.

00:32:00.257 --> 00:32:01.840
So it's those kind
of moments that let

00:32:01.840 --> 00:32:03.648
me know I'm in the right place.

00:32:03.648 --> 00:32:05.940
And going back to the beginning
and doing these plays--

00:32:05.940 --> 00:32:09.460
back when I started, there
was a Mama on the Couch play

00:32:09.460 --> 00:32:09.960
everywhere.

00:32:09.960 --> 00:32:11.715
That's we called them,
Mama on the Couch.

00:32:11.715 --> 00:32:13.810
(FEMALE VOICE) Mama,
my man left me.

00:32:13.810 --> 00:32:15.880
Mama, Jesus is real.

00:32:15.880 --> 00:32:17.995
Mama, where is my
shoes, you know?

00:32:17.995 --> 00:32:19.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:19.060 --> 00:32:21.740
So I started putting my
name on it in front of it,

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:23.792
like Tyler Perry's--

00:32:23.792 --> 00:32:25.000
I went a little far with it--

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:26.580
but it was Tyler Perry's,
Tyler Perry, Tyler Perry,

00:32:26.580 --> 00:32:27.402
Tyler Perry.

00:32:27.402 --> 00:32:29.110
And the audience
started to recognize it,

00:32:29.110 --> 00:32:31.235
and they started identifying
that when you see his,

00:32:31.235 --> 00:32:34.353
it's going to be more than a
piece of plywood on the stage.

00:32:34.353 --> 00:32:35.770
Because man, in
these shows, there

00:32:35.770 --> 00:32:38.280
was a sofa, a piece of plywood--

00:32:38.280 --> 00:32:39.640
some of y'all been to 'em--

00:32:39.640 --> 00:32:42.610
and a couple of speakers
from your mama's house trying

00:32:42.610 --> 00:32:44.740
to do the sound in the theater.

00:32:44.740 --> 00:32:46.755
But trying to raise
that and elevate it

00:32:46.755 --> 00:32:47.880
was really important to me.

00:32:47.880 --> 00:32:50.513
So to see how far
it's come now--

00:32:50.513 --> 00:32:52.930
